  <body id="msgFeedSummaryBody" selected="false">
    <div class="field field-name-field-image field-type-image field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" rel="og:image rdfs:seeAlso" resource="https://www.softinn.eu/sites/softinn.pl/files/styles/medium/public/field/image/FB-ThumbsUp_512.png?itok=a5BbOgEb"><a href="/en/blog/how-login-drupal-facebook-account"><img typeof="foaf:Image" src="https://www.softinn.eu/sites/softinn.pl/files/styles/medium/public/field/image/FB-ThumbsUp_512.png?itok=a5BbOgEb" width="220" height="194" alt="" /></a></div></div></div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"><p>I'm a big fan of single-sign on (SSO) systems. Keeping one account secure and up-to-date is much easier than dealing with hundreds of logins and passwords for hundreds of sites. Fortunately, many of our clients agree with that and introduce single-sign on mechanisms on their sites and apps.</p>
<p>The most popular choice for SSO nowadays is to use Facebook as identity provider. Fortunately, Facebook authentication is quite well supported by Drupal. </p>
